Lipid peroxidation is extremely harmful and occurs as a self-sustaining chain reaction. Reactive oxygen species are thought to cause cell damage through the production of free radicals and lipid peroxide radicals in cell membranes.39 With a few minor adjustments, the lipid peroxidation inhibition experiment was carried out as specified in method.40 The synthesized compounds were homogenized using the homogenizer, and the supernatant was used for the assay. The Thiobarbituric acid-Trichloroacetic acid (TBA-TCA) mixture was prepared by dissolving 0.392 g TBA in 75 mL of 0.25 M HCl, followed by the addition of 5 g TCA, and made up to 100 mL of 0.25 M HCl. In this assay, 500 mL of the TBA-TCA mixture was added to a mixture containing 250 mL of homogenate and 200 mL PBS buffer, in a clean test tube. These test tubes were covered with aluminum foil and boiled in a water bath at 100 °C for 30 min. The mixture was allowed to cool at room temperature, centrifuged at 2000 rpm for 10 min and the supernatant was transferred into a 96-microwell plate. Absorbance was read on a microplate reader at 540 nm. Ascorbic acid was used as a positive control. The percentage of lipid peroxidation inhibition was calculated from the following equation:
